  "prompt": "What are the types of scholarships for international undergraduate students who don\u2019t have concerns with housing?",
  "response": "There are several types of scholarships available for international undergraduate students who do not have concerns with housing. These scholarships can be categorized based on their sources and criteria:\n\n1. **Merit-Based Scholarships**: These scholarships are awarded based on academic excellence, standardized test scores, extracurricular achievements, and other accomplishments. Examples include:\n   - University-specific merit scholarships\n   - National merit scholarships\n   - Private organization scholarships\n\n2. **Need-Based Scholarships**: These scholarships are awarded based on the financial need of the student. Even if housing costs are not a concern, students might still qualify for other types of financial assistance. Examples include:\n   - University-specific need-based scholarships\n   - Government-funded need-based scholarships\n\n3. **Subject-Specific Scholarships**: These scholarships are awarded to students pursuing specific fields of study such as science, technology, engineering, mathematics (STEM), humanities, arts, etc. Examples include:\n   - Scholarships for STEM majors\n   - Scholarships for arts and humanities\n\n4. **Country-Specific Scholarships**: These scholarships are offered to students from specific countries or regions. Examples include:\n   - Fulbright Program (for students from various countries)\n   - Chevening Scholarships (for students from Chevening-eligible countries)\n\n5. **Athletic Scholarships**: These scholarships are awarded to students who excel in sports. They are often provided by universities with strong athletic programs. Examples include:\n   - NCAA scholarships\n   - University-specific athletic scholarships\n\n6. **Diversity Scholarships**: These scholarships aim to promote diversity within the student body and can be awarded based on ethnicity, gender, sexual orientation, etc. Examples include:\n   - Scholarships for underrepresented minorities\n   - Women in STEM scholarships\n\n7. **Creative and Performing Arts Scholarships**: These scholarships are for students who excel in areas like music, theater, film, visual arts, and other creative disciplines. Examples include:\n   - Scholarships for visual arts\n   - Scholarships for performing arts\n\n8. **Community Service Scholarships**: These scholarships are awarded to students who have demonstrated significant involvement in community service and volunteer work. Examples include:\n   - Scholarships from community organizations\n   - University-specific community service scholarships\n\n9. **Research Scholarships**: These scholarships are awarded to students who have shown potential in research and wish to pursue undergraduate research projects. Examples include:\n   - University-specific research scholarships\n   - Scholarships from research foundations\n\n10. **Company-Sponsored Scholarships**: Many corporations and businesses offer scholarships to students pursuing degrees related to their industry. Examples include:\n    - Scholarships from tech companies\n    - Scholarships from financial institutions\n\nIt is important for students to research specific eligibility criteria and application procedures for each scholarship. Universities typically have dedicated offices or websites providing detailed information on available scholarships for international students. Additionally, organizations like EducationUSA can offer guidance and resources for finding scholarships suitable for international students.",
